	   <a name=96878658829333></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96878658829333><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96878658829333>Spells for running away.</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96878658829333#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Sep 12th 3:23 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>You mention several spells for running away.&nbsp;&nbsp;Over time, I have found some of them more useful than others.<br><br>1.  Divine Aura / Divine Barrier.  These spells are your first line of defense when retreating.  If the zone line is close, they are your best bet.  NOTE:  You are likely to get stunned once or twice while running, especially if the mob is red to you.  Be sure to add extra time in to your retreat if the mob is likely to stop you for a few seconds due to stuns.  DA/DB is also the very best choice spell to get out of a sticky situation if the chasing mob is a caster.<br><br>2.  Root.  When crossing large zones, rooting green and blue mobs is your VERY best choice for a fast continue.  Root and run and forget about them.  By the time the root wears off, you'll be out of aggro range, and you can continue your way to the next zone.  This strategy is dangerous if you do NOT plan to zone soon, since mobs will be angry at you, and that can come back to haunt you minutes or even hours down the road.<br><br>3.  Stun.  Our stuns are short, and simply don't provide enough of a head-start to be helpful for a retreat.  Unless you are stunning to buy enough time to root, I don't see a real use for stuns in fleeing.<br><br>4.  Fear.  Be sure to realize that fearing WILL cause massive trains in dungeons.  MASSIVE trains.  If you fear, you'd better be heading for the zone line, because everything in the dungeon will be mad at you, and expressing their displeasure in the near future.<br><br>You forgot the most important tool for the fleeing cleric:<br><br>5.  Gate.  When your party is overwhelmed, let the tanks run for the zone line.  Heal them until they are out of range, and then gate.  (You DID remember to bind yourself just outside the dungeon, didn't you?)  This is the best way of escape, since you don't even have to FACE the mobs -- they'll be beating on your tanks while you sneak out the back way.<br><br>-Kinter<br>51st level Cleric, Prexus Server<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
